{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e06e441f-0470-4259-97f0-6bbcf3bb5c23","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, so this is a guidance question rather than a \"fix my project\" task. Here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj`:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for …</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n1. **`PackAsTool`** — marks the project as a .NET tool (must be a console app with `OutputType=Exe`).\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI name users will invoke (e.g., `my-mcp-server`).\n3. **Pack & publish:**\n   ```bash\n   dotnet pack -c Release\n   dotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n     --api-key YOUR_NUGET_API_KEY \\\n     --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n   ```\n4. **Users install with:**\n   ```bash\n   dotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\n   ```\n\nThat's it — `PackAsTool` + `ToolCommandName` are the two critical settings that turn a normal console app into an installable dotnet tool. Everything else is standard NuGet package metadata.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"71be98c5-a516-4b09-b2b3-ab333c69f28d","outputTokens":454},"id":"7ca0122a-95bc-4e6a-8410-3f2694c7ed6b","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:53:30.370Z","parentId":"17968ca5-60f9-4083-b85d-12993fb011ba"}
